    "summary": "Yes, two notes — line 17 primes, line 25 pays off",
    "content": "**Yes, two notes.** The author already provides the primer at line 17 -- the parenthetical（界限）is itself a gloss. The translator's note simply makes the 境 component visible to the English reader, which the Chinese reader already sees. This is not adding information; it is preserving information that the original provides for free through character transparency.\n\nBrief at line 17, deeper at line 25. The line 17 note primes; the line 25 note pays off. Without the primer, the line 25 payoff arrives cold and the reader has to do two things at once (learn the etymology AND see the conceptual separation). With the primer, the reader already has the components and line 25 becomes a moment of recognition -- which is, fittingly, exactly how the author describes understanding (η as direct confirmation).\n"
